COVID-19 pandemic in Turkey

location

Climate condition

Although Turkey is situated in a geographical location where climatic conditions are quite temperate diverse nature of the landscape, and the existence in particular of the mountains that run parallel to the coasts, result in significant differences in climatic conditions from one region to the other. While the coastal areas enjoy milder climates, the inland Anatolian plateau experiences extremes of hot summers and cold winters with limited rainfall. Turkey receives most of the rainfall in the winter season. In this season, mean temperature usually is below 5 and there is no too much evaporation. But summer rainfall is very limited and could not be enough to remove water deficit resulted from increased temperature and evaporation. The Aegean and Mediterranean coasts have cool, rainy winters and hot, moderately dry summers. Annual precipitation in those areas varies from 580 to 1,300 millimeters, depending on location. The Black Sea coast receives the greatest amount of rainfall. The eastern part of that receives 2,200 millimeters annually and is the only region of Turkey that receives rainfall throughout the year.

Lockdown status in Turkey

The disease was confirmed to have reached Turkey on 11 March 2020, after a man who had returned to Turkey from Europe, tested positive.The first death due to COVID-19 in the country occurred on 15 March 2020 and by 1 April, it was confirmed that COVID-19 had spread all over Turkey On 14 April 2020,On 1 February, Turkey announced its decision to stop all the flights from China. One of the first measures taken by the government was the declaration of curfew for the 65-year-old and older group, which is likely to be the most affected by the virus. This ban was recently extended to cover the under-20 group. Limited to the age range of 18-20, those who work in public institutions or in private sector that have not switched to distance working and some seasonal agricultural workers are exempted from this prohibition. Additionally, as of March 29, 2020, passengers will no longer be able to travel with airlines and busses without a travel permit. This statement was expanded to a ban on entry and exit for all vehicles, including personal vehicles, to 30 provinces with metropolitan status and Zonguldak province, with a memorandum issued by the Ministry of Interior. Exemptions of this prohibition include those who were discharged from the hospital where they were treated, those who travelled to attend the funeral of their first-degree relatives and those who came to the city in the last 5 days and have no accommodation, those who completed military service, and those who were released from prisons.

Action taken by goverment

Education

On 8 March, the Ministry of National Education announced that they were using special disinfectants to keep schools clean against the virus threat after that all schools in Turkey would be closed starting from 16 March 2020 for a week. The remote classes for primary, secondary and high schools started on 23 March 2020 on TRT EBA TV, a channel created through the collaboration of TRT and the Ministry of Education

Travel Restriction

Turkey closed all board gates and announced that pavilions, discotheques, bars and night clubs would be closed temporarily starting from 10:00 on 16 March, On 16 March announced a nationwide ban on prayer gatherings in mosques, including Friday prayers, due to the pandemic and temporarily closing all public gathering places such as cafes, gyms, Internet cafes and movie theaters, except shops and restaurants not offering music, starting midnight the following day

Economics

Turkey goverment announced stated that public banks will deliver pensions to retirees above the age of 76 to their homes, with the minimum amount of payment for retired people being ???1,500.The Banks Association of Turkey also sent a notice to different banks across the country and limited their working hours to 12:00 pm to 5:00 pm, which went into effect on 23 March 2020.Some of the economic measures taken by the Turkish government are; describing the pandemic as a force majeure event as per public procurement contracts, postponement of general assembly meetings, limitations on dividend distribution, flexibility on rent payments, modification on short time working and compensatory work rules, export control on disinfectants, medical diagnostic kits, masks and intensive care equipment.
